Gemini said
It looks like you've got a solid, modular setup going! However, there is one glaring "copy-paste" ghost in the machine that is definitely breaking things, plus a few structural tweaks to make it more robust.

1. The "URL" Bug
In your EDITOR export, you have a URL accidentally pasted into the middle of the line:
export EDITOR=nvimhttps://pages.tobi.lutke.com/try/

The Fix:

Bash
export EDITOR='nvim'
export VISUAL='nvim'
Without fixing this, any program trying to launch your editor (like git commit) will fail because it's looking for a binary named nvimhttps://....

2. The load_if_present Pathing
In your load_if_present function, you aren't quoting the variable $1. If you ever have a path with a space in it, the script will throw an error.

The Fix:

Bash
load_if_present() {
    [ -f "$1" ] && . "$1"
}
3. Starship & Zoxide Performance
You are using eval "$(starship init bash)". While this works perfectly, it can slightly slow down the shell startup because it has to run the starship binary just to generate the setup code every single time you open a terminal.

Pro-tip: Most power users eventually cache these or just accept the tiny delay. Your current way is "correct," but ensure these tools are actually installed on the system, or the .bashrc will throw "command not found" errors on startup.

Optimized Version
Here is the cleaned-up section of your config:

Bash
# ... (interactive check remains the same)

# 1. Fixed the URL typo and added quotes
export EDITOR='nvim'
export VISUAL='nvim'

# 2. Improved function with quoted variable
load_if_present() {
    [ -f "$1" ] && . "$1"
}

# 3. Secret vars
load_if_present "$HOME/thunderseed/secretConfig/bash/bashrc_env_vars"

# 4. Imports
BASH_CONF_DIR="$HOME/.config/bash"
load_bashrc_part() {
    load_if_present "$BASH_CONF_DIR/$1"
}

load_bashrc_part "aliases"
load_bashrc_part "functions"
load_bashrc_part "completions"
load_bashrc_part "options"

# 5. Initializations (Ensure these binaries exist!)
if command -v starship >/dev/null; then eval "$(starship init bash)"; fi
if command -v zoxide >/dev/null; then eval "$(zoxide init bash)"; fi
[ -f ~/.fzf.bash ] && source ~/.fzf.bash # Standard fzf init or keep your eval
